---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "Sig Fig Calculator — Find Significant Figures Instantly",
  description: "Stop losing points on chemistry homework. Our sig fig calculator instantly formats numbers and expressions with the correct rules.",
  category: "tool",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};

const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": meta.title,
    "description": meta.description,
    "datePublished": meta.published,
    "author": {
      "@type": "Organization",
      "name": "SiliconBased"
    }
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "Are leading zeros significant?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                  "@type": "Answer",
                  "text": "No, leading zeros are never considered significant figures. Zeros that come before the first non-zero digit are simply placeholders that locate the decimal point. For example, in the number 0.0034, only the 3 and the 4 are significant, meaning the number has two significant figures in total."
            }
      },
      {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "Are trailing zeros significant?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                  "@type": "Answer",
                  "text": "It depends entirely on the presence of a decimal point. If a number contains a decimal point, any trailing zeros are significant (e.g., 4.500 has four sig figs). If the number does not contain a decimal point, trailing zeros are generally considered not significant (e.g., 4500 has two sig figs)."
            }
      },
      {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "How do I handle significant figures in scientific notation?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                  "@type": "Answer",
                  "text": "Scientific notation makes significant figures very easy to determine. You simply count the digits in the coefficient (the number before the multiplication sign) and entirely ignore the exponent base part. For example, in the value 6.022 x 10^23, the coefficient is 6.022. Counting those digits gives you four significant figures."
            }
      },
      {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "What is the rule for multiplication and division?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                  "@type": "Answer",
                  "text": "When multiplying or dividing, your final answer must be rounded to match the input value that has the fewest total significant figures. If you multiply a value with 4 sig figs by a value with 2 sig figs, your final answer can only legally have 2 sig figs, regardless of how many decimal places the raw math produces."
            }
      },
      {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "What is the rule for addition and subtraction?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                  "@type": "Answer",
                  "text": "Unlike multiplication, addition and subtraction rules focus on decimal placement rather than the total count of digits. Your final answer must be rounded to the same number of decimal places as the input value with the fewest decimal places. For instance, 10.5 + 2.15 = 12.65, but must be rounded to 12.7 because 10.5 only has one decimal place."
            }
      }
]
  }
];
---
<SiteLayout site="siliconbased" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://siliconbased.dev/sig-fig-calculator" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>{meta.title}</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Calculate significant figures for numbers and expressions accurately</p>
    </div>

    <div class="calculator-container">
      <div class="form-group">
        <label for="numberInput">Enter a number</label>
        <input type="text" id="numberInput" placeholder="e.g., 0.00450, 1020, 3.14e-5">
        <div id="inputError" class="error-msg">Please enter a valid number (scientific notation like 1.2e3 is supported).</div>
      </div>

      <div class="form-group">
        <label for="roundInput">Round to significant figures (optional)</label>
        <input type="number" id="roundInput" min="1" step="1" placeholder="e.g., 3">
        <div id="roundError" class="error-msg">Please enter a valid positive integer.</div>
      </div>

      <div id="resultCard" class="result-card">
        <div class="result-label" id="resultLabel">Significant Figures</div>
        <div id="sigFigCount" class="result-value">--</div>

        <div id="roundedContainer" style="display: none; margin-top: 1.5rem; padding-top: 1.5rem; border-top: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 30%, transparent);">
          <div class="result-label">Rounded Value</div>
          <div id="roundedValue" class="result-value" style="font-size: 2rem;">--</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="explainer">
      <h2>The Definitive Guide to Significant Figures</h2>
      <p>Whether you are balancing complex chemical equations, calculating projectile motion in physics, or simply trying to pass your next introductory science exam, understanding significant figures (often abbreviated as "sig figs") is an absolute necessity. Significant figures are the digits in a number that carry meaning contributing to its precision. They provide a standardized way for scientists, engineers, and mathematicians to communicate the exactness of a measurement. When you say a table is "2 meters long" versus "2.00 meters long," you are conveying vastly different levels of certainty. The first implies a rough estimate, perhaps measured by pacing it out, while the latter implies a highly precise measurement, likely taken with a calibrated tape measure. Our sig fig calculator is built to help you instantly identify the correct number of significant digits in any given value and round complex calculations without second-guessing yourself.</p>

      <p>The concept of significant figures stems from the inherent limitations of measuring instruments. No analog tool is perfectly precise. If you use a standard classroom ruler to measure a block of wood, you might clearly see it extends past the 14-centimeter mark and past the 6-millimeter mark, but it falls somewhere between 14.6 cm and 14.7 cm. You must estimate that final digit—perhaps guessing it is 14.63 cm. In this measurement, the 1, 4, and 6 are certain digits, and the 3 is the single estimated digit. In scientific recording, a proper measurement includes all certain digits plus exactly one estimated digit. All of these digits, combined, are your significant figures.</p>

      <h3>The Core Rules of Significant Figures</h3>
      <p>To accurately count significant figures, you must master a specific set of rules regarding which digits matter, particularly when dealing with zeros. Zeros are the most frequent source of confusion because they serve two distinct purposes: they can be part of the actual measured value, or they can merely act as placeholders to locate the decimal point. Here are the unbreakable rules:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Non-Zero Digits:</strong> Every single non-zero digit (1 through 9) is always significant. For example, the number 4,582 has four significant figures.</li>
        <li><strong>Captive Zeros:</strong> Any zeros sandwiched between non-zero digits are always significant. They are an integral part of the measurement. The number 50.003 has five significant figures.</li>
        <li><strong>Leading Zeros:</strong> Zeros that precede all non-zero digits are never significant. They are simply placeholders indicating the scale of the number. The value 0.00045 only has two significant figures (the 4 and the 5).</li>
        <li><strong>Trailing Zeros with a Decimal:</strong> Zeros at the end of a number are significant <em>only if</em> the number contains a explicitly written decimal point. For example, 3.200 has four significant figures, because those trailing zeros indicate a high level of precision.</li>
        <li><strong>Trailing Zeros without a Decimal:</strong> If a number ends in zeros but lacks a decimal point, those zeros are generally considered ambiguous and are not counted as significant. The number 45,000 has only two significant figures. If you wanted to show that the thousands place was accurately measured, you would write it in scientific notation as 4.50 &times; 10<sup>4</sup>.</li>
        <li><strong>Exact Numbers:</strong> Certain values, such as counted quantities (e.g., exactly 12 apples) or defined constants (e.g., 1 inch = exactly 2.54 cm), possess an infinite number of significant figures. They do not restrict the precision of your calculated results.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Performing Calculations with Significant Figures</h3>
      <p>The rules shift slightly when you begin performing mathematical operations. It is crucial to remember that your final calculated answer can never be more precise than your least precise initial measurement. A chain is only as strong as its weakest link, and an equation is only as precise as its worst measurement.</p>

      <p>When you are multiplying or dividing numbers, the rule dictates that your final answer must have the same number of significant figures as the original value with the <em>fewest</em> significant figures. For example, if you multiply 4.56 (which has three sig figs) by 1.4 (which has two sig figs), your raw calculator output is 6.384. However, because your least precise input only had two significant figures, you must round your final answer to two significant figures, resulting in 6.4.</p>

      <p>Addition and subtraction follow a different logic. When adding or subtracting, you do not count total significant figures; instead, you look at the decimal places. Your final answer cannot have more decimal places than the original measurement with the fewest decimal places. If you add 12.11 (two decimal places) to 18.0 (one decimal place) to 1.013 (three decimal places), the raw sum is 31.123. Because 18.0 is only precise to the tenths place, your final answer must be rounded to the tenths place, yielding 31.1.</p>

      <h3>Why This Calculator is Essential for Students</h3>
      <p>Applying these rules simultaneously during a lengthy chemistry or physics exam can lead to cognitive overload and easily preventable point deductions. Many students perfectly understand the underlying scientific concepts but lose letter grades on their final exams simply due to rounding errors or miscounting captive zeros. This calculator serves as an instant verification tool. By allowing you to input complex numbers—including scientific notation—and see both the exact significant figure count and the correctly rounded result, it reinforces the rules through immediate feedback. Regular use of this tool while completing homework will help internalize the logic of precision, ensuring that when test day arrives, handling significant figures is second nature rather than a stumbling block.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="related-tools" style="margin: 2rem 0; padding: 1.5rem; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 12px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);">
      <h3 style="margin-bottom: 1rem; font-size: 1.25rem;">Related Tools</h3>
      <p>Check out our <a href="/rl-tracker" style="color: var(--accent-color); font-weight: 600; text-decoration: none;">RL Tracker</a> to crunch the numbers on your ranking stats.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>Are leading zeros significant?</summary>
        <p>No, leading zeros are never considered significant figures. Zeros that come before the first non-zero digit are simply placeholders that locate the decimal point. For example, in the number 0.0034, only the 3 and the 4 are significant, meaning the number has two significant figures in total.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Are trailing zeros significant?</summary>
        <p>It depends entirely on the presence of a decimal point. If a number contains a decimal point, any trailing zeros are significant (e.g., 4.500 has four sig figs). If the number does not contain a decimal point, trailing zeros are generally considered not significant (e.g., 4500 has two sig figs).</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How do I handle significant figures in scientific notation?</summary>
        <p>Scientific notation makes significant figures very easy to determine. You simply count the digits in the coefficient (the number before the multiplication sign) and entirely ignore the exponent base part. For example, in the value 6.022 x 10^23, the coefficient is 6.022. Counting those digits gives you four significant figures.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the rule for multiplication and division?</summary>
        <p>When multiplying or dividing, your final answer must be rounded to match the input value that has the fewest total significant figures. If you multiply a value with 4 sig figs by a value with 2 sig figs, your final answer can only legally have 2 sig figs, regardless of how many decimal places the raw math produces.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the rule for addition and subtraction?</summary>
        <p>Unlike multiplication, addition and subtraction rules focus on decimal placement rather than the total count of digits. Your final answer must be rounded to the same number of decimal places as the input value with the fewest decimal places. For instance, 10.5 + 2.15 = 12.65, but must be rounded to 12.7 because 10.5 only has one decimal place.</p>
      </details>
    </section>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
      const numberInput = document.getElementById('numberInput');
      const roundInput = document.getElementById('roundInput');

      const inputError = document.getElementById('inputError');
      const roundError = document.getElementById('roundError');

      const resultCard = document.getElementById('resultCard');
      const sigFigCount = document.getElementById('sigFigCount');
      const roundedContainer = document.getElementById('roundedContainer');
      const roundedValueDisplay = document.getElementById('roundedValue');

      // Remove commas and spaces for processing
      function cleanInput(str) {
        return str.replace(/[, ]/g, '').trim();
      }

      // Determine number of sig figs
      function countSigFigs(numStr) {
        // Handle scientific notation e.g. 1.23e4
        const sciRegex = /^([-+]?[0-9]*\.?[0-9]+)[eE]([-+]?[0-9]+)$/;
        const sciMatch = numStr.match(sciRegex);

        let mantissa = numStr;
        if (sciMatch) {
          mantissa = sciMatch[1];
        }

        // Remove negative sign
        if (mantissa.startsWith('-') || mantissa.startsWith('+')) {
          mantissa = mantissa.substring(1);
        }

        // Not a number check
        if (!/^[0-9]*\.?[0-9]+$/.test(mantissa)) {
          return -1;
        }

        if (mantissa.includes('.')) {
          // Rule: With a decimal point, leading zeros are not significant
          // Example: 0.00450 -> 450 (3 sig figs)
          // Strip leading zeros (including before and immediately after decimal if no non-zeros exist yet)
          let trimmed = mantissa.replace(/^0+/, '');

          if (trimmed.startsWith('.')) {
             // 0.0045 -> .0045 -> strip leading zeros after decimal
             trimmed = trimmed.substring(1).replace(/^0+/, '');
          } else {
             // 10.0 -> remove decimal for counting
             trimmed = trimmed.replace('.', '');
          }

          if (trimmed === '') {
             // It was just zeros (e.g. 0.00)
             // The zeros after the decimal ARE significant if it's explicitly written like 0.0
             // But usually 0 is 1 sig fig or ambiguous. Let's count explicitly written zeros.
             const zeroMatch = mantissa.match(/\.(0+)/);
             return zeroMatch ? zeroMatch[1].length : 1;
          }

          return trimmed.length;
        } else {
          // Rule: Without a decimal, trailing zeros are NOT significant
          // Example: 1200 -> 12 (2 sig figs)
          // Remove leading zeros just in case
          let trimmed = mantissa.replace(/^0+/, '');
          if (trimmed === '') return 1; // It was just '0'

          trimmed = trimmed.replace(/0+$/, '');
          return trimmed.length;
        }
      }

      function toSignificantFigures(num, n) {
        if (num === 0) return (0).toFixed(n - 1);

        const d = Math.ceil(Math.log10(num < 0 ? -num : num));
        const power = n - d;
        const magnitude = Math.pow(10, power);
        const shifted = Math.round(num * magnitude);

        // Handle floating point precision issues gracefully
        let result = (shifted / magnitude).toPrecision(n);

        // Convert back to standard notation if toPrecision returned scientific for small/large but not requested
        return result;
      }

      function calculate() {
        const rawStr = numberInput.value;
        const roundStr = roundInput.value;

        inputError.style.display = 'none';
        roundError.style.display = 'none';

        if (rawStr.trim() === '') {
          resultCard.style.display = 'none';
          return;
        }

        const cleanStr = cleanInput(rawStr);
        const sigFigs = countSigFigs(cleanStr);

        let hasError = false;

        if (sigFigs === -1) {
          inputError.style.display = 'block';
          hasError = true;
        }

        let roundTarget = null;
        if (roundStr.trim() !== '') {
          roundTarget = parseInt(roundStr, 10);
          if (isNaN(roundTarget) || roundTarget < 1) {
            roundError.style.display = 'block';
            hasError = true;
          }
        }

        if (hasError) {
          resultCard.style.display = 'none';
          return;
        }

        sigFigCount.textContent = sigFigs;

        if (roundTarget !== null) {
          const numValue = parseFloat(cleanStr);
          roundedValueDisplay.textContent = toSignificantFigures(numValue, roundTarget);
          roundedContainer.style.display = 'block';
        } else {
          roundedContainer.style.display = 'none';
        }

        resultCard.style.display = 'block';
      }

      numberInput.addEventListener('input', calculate);
      roundInput.addEventListener('input', calculate);
    });
  </script>

  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .subtitle { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; }
    .calculator-container { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 2rem; margin: 2rem 0; }

    .form-group { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
    .form-group label { display: block; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text-primary); }

    input, select { background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding: 0.75rem 1rem; border-radius: 8px; width: 100%; font-size: 1rem; }
    input:focus, select:focus { outline: none; border-color: var(--accent-color); box-shadow: 0 0 0 3px color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 20%, transparent); }

    .error-msg { color: #ef4444; font-size: 0.875rem; margin-top: 0.5rem; display: none; }

    button { background: var(--accent-color); color: white; border: none; padding: 0.75rem 2rem; border-radius: 8px; font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; font-size: 1rem; }
    button:hover { opacity: 0.9; }

    .result-card { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 10%, transparent); border: 1px solid var(--accent-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; text-align: center; display: none; }
    .result-value { font-size: 2.5rem; font-weight: 800; color: var(--accent-color); margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .result-label { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; }

    .explainer { margin: 3rem 0; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .explainer h2 { font-size: 1.8rem; margin: 2rem 0 1rem; }
    .explainer h3 { font-size: 1.4rem; margin: 1.5rem 0 0.5rem; }
    .explainer p { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
    .explainer ul { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; padding-left: 1.5rem; }
    .explainer li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }

    .faq-section details { margin: 1rem 0; padding: 1rem; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .faq-section summary { font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; list-style-position: inside; }
    .faq-section p { margin-top: 1rem; margin-bottom: 0; line-height: 1.6; }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
